---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const adventures = [
  {
    title: "Cape Town Cycle Tour",
    date: "March 2026",
    location: "Cape Town, Western Cape",
    body:
      `One of my favourite experiences is the Cape Town Cycle Tour. If you told me 2 years ago
      that I would be able to cycle 109km I would have told you that you are out of your mind.
      It all started with my mother that loves cycling, she used to beg me to just try it out,
      eventually I gave in and started cycling with her. I was quickly humbled, but I slowly started 
      to enjoy it. Eventually I upgraded to cleat shoes. These are shoes that cyclists use to keep 
      their feet bound to the pedals. I took a few nasty falls trying to figure it out, but I kept
      on cycling. Before the actual race, we did a seeding race. This race was 95km, I was scared but
      excited. The race went surprisingly well, and I enjoyed it. 
      The day of the Cycle Tour came around. It was 4 of us that stuck in a group. My parents, myself 
      and my boyfriend. The race started of freezing cold and so many people was bundled around me.
      I had to have complete consentration the whole time other wise I might crash, there was a few
      close calls. As we continued the wind picked up, but we were still fine. Eventually the 2 men went
      ahead so it was just my mom and I. A round 80 km I got a puncture! A tiny needle was in my tyre! 
      What would be the odds of my riding into a needle? Literally a needle in a haystack. I was 
      upset immediately. It was just my mom and I, neither of us has had much experience with tube changing.
      We stood there for a few minutes, we saw an ambulance and walked closer. None of them offered to help.
      After a few minutes, a man came to us and asked if we had a spare tube. We gave our other tube to him.
      After he changed his own tube, he came to help us. We were so thankful. After that we were on the
      road again. With 20 minutes wasted, BUT now we had knowledge on how to change a tube.
      Those last few kilometers were tough, everything was aching. But I pushed through, I was determined
      to end strong. In the end it was amazing, I felt so proud of myself for overcoming all the hurdles.
      I cannot wait to try again next year. `,
  },
  {
    title: "Xterra",
    date: "Feb 2025",
    location: "Grabouw, Western Cape",
    body:
      "",
  },
  {
    title: "Harbour to Harbour Swim",
    date: "May 2024",
    location: "Gordons Bay, Western Cape",
    body:
      'I used to swim in highschool as a sport, during covid I was forced to stop and eventually I lost my love for the sport.
      After having a tough academic year in 2023, I decided that I need to do something different! I slowly started to swim again.
      Swimming is so peaceful, its where you can just be by yourself and process your thoughts, no noise, just you the water and that black line.
      I eventually started to feel nostalgic, I started to miss competing. I decided to sign up for the Harbour to Harbour mile ocean swim in 
      Gordons Bay. I trained early mornings before class or in the evenings after class. Training by myself started to become tough, especially
      in the mornings when it is cold. When the day of the swim came, the realisation of the May cold kicked in! At least I had a wetsuit! 
      The water was cold, but calm. The start is always the hard part in an open water swim, everyone is kicking and arms are flying, you 
      just want to get away from everyone. As time went on I felt good and the cold was not bothering me too much. The ocean was so clear I could
      see to the bottom of the ocean, it was beautiful! Suddenly I realised that I was mostly alone, I was in between the front pack and the pack behind me.
      The unrealistic fear of a shark suddenly appeariing kicked in, but the thousands and thousands of beautiful starfish at the bottom helped me to get 
      through it. I finally reached the end! And it was so rewarding! I felt so proud of my self for overcoming the fears I had.',
  },
  {
    title: "Skydive",
    date: "",
    location: "Mosselbay, Western Cape",
    body:
      "",
  },
];
---

<Layout title="Adventures — Gabriella Scott">
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">Adventures</h1>

  <p class="mt-3 max-w-2xl text-ink/70">
    I love to experience new things that gets the heart pumping and the blood flowing. Here are some of my
    favourite adventures that I will never forget.
  </p>

  <section class="mt-12">
    <div class="mt-8 space-y-8">
      {adventures.map((a) => (
        <article class="fade-up rounded-2xl bg-sky/20 p-6">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap items-baseline gap-x-3">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold">{a.title}</h3>
            <span class="font-handwriting text-lg text-ink/60">{a.location}</span>
          </div>
          <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-ink/50">{a.date}</p>
          <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-ink/80">{a.body}</p>
          {a.title === "Cape Town Cycle Tour" && (
            <div class="mt-5 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
              <img src="/Cycle1.JPG" alt="Cape Town Cycle Tour photo 1" class="h-48 w-auto rounded-xl object-cover" />
              <img src="/Cycle2.JPG" alt="Cape Town Cycle Tour photo 2" class="h-48 w-auto rounded-xl object-cover" />
              <img src="/Cycle3.JPG" alt="Cape Town Cycle Tour photo 3" class="h-48 w-auto rounded-xl object-cover" />
              <video src="/Cycle_vid.MP4" autoplay loop muted playsinline class="h-48 w-auto rounded-xl object-cover" />
            </div>
          )}
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .fade-up { animation: fade-up 0.6s ease-out both; }
  @keyframes fade-up {
    from { opacity: 0; transform: translateY(12px); }
    to   { opacity: 1; transform: translateY(0); }
  }
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    .fade-up { animation: none; }
  }
</style>